    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-14T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-14T05:00:00-05:00" n="717"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d717">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.00B <persName>Rubens, Adolph A.</persName>/51:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_GSE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grummon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-14T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 14, 1939—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 14—9:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>311. Following the interview with <persName corresp="#p_RAA1">Rosh</persName>
                    reported in my 308 June 12, 2 p.m.,<note n="33" xml:id="d717fn33">Not
                        printed.</note> inquiry was made again yesterday of
                        <persName>Mikhailov</persName>, Chief of the Consular Section and of
                    Sobelev, Referent of the Third Western Division of the Commissariat for Foreign
                    Affairs regarding Mrs. <persName>Rubens</persName>’ whereabouts.
                        <persName>Mikhailov</persName> stated that he was not occupying himself with
                    the matter. Sobelev stated that the normal procedure would be to take up such
                    matters with <persName>Mikhailov</persName> and denied that <persName
                        corresp="#p_RAA1">Rosh</persName> had referred the matter to him for his
                    attention. In view of the apparent intentional evasiveness of the Commissariat
                    for Foreign Affairs in regard to Mrs. <persName>Rubens</persName>’ whereabouts
                    and the probability that further informal inquiries will continue to be
                    unavailing I should appreciate an indication as to the Department’s wishes
                    regarding future representations on this matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grummon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
